explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf mutant results in proteins that affect the ATP function of the histones and DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation control gene function in eukaryotes. During acetylation, the histones interactions are relaxed and euchromatin forms, allowing the DNA to be transcribed. In deacetylation, the reverse takes place, and the genes are silenced.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] I've been familiar with heterochromatin and euchromatin for a long time but never knew that one heterochromatin could be relaxed to form euchromatin and thus be transcribed.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] The complexity of eukaryotes by comparison to prokaryotes (organelles, meiotic division, etc.) is a reflection of their gene transcription as well. The overwhelming complexity of gene silencing and regulation in eukaryotes shows the immense difference in these two types of cells.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The gene regulation in eukaryotes is more highly specified than the process that occurs in prokaryotes. Not only does eukaryotes have more DNA than prokaryotes, but the DNA has histones and other protein complexes that help affect the regulation of gene expression. Eukaryotic mRNA also has an immense process that it must pass through.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The normal SWI/SNF works by rearranging the components that make up a nucleosome. Obviously a mutant of the SWI/SNF is going to cause an error in the repositioning and attachment of the nucleosome. In the example, the mutant eukaryote was not able to ferment sucrose.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Hyperacetylation (profound amounts of acetyl groups added) of nucleosome tails promotes gene activity and deacetylation or hypoacetylation (lack of acetyl groups) promotes gene inactivity. This occurs through proteins HAT (Histone acetyltransferase gene) and HDAC (Histone deacetylation gene).
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] I think this is really interesting because we focused a lot on the topic of acetylation and methylation in lab this week. It is intriguing because there are several ways to promote and stop gene expression.
phenomenonB The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonB[comment] This is interesting because it is a specific example of a mutation that effects the fermentation of sucrose in Saccharomyces. It is interesting to be able to relate a mutation to a physical effect.
groupTime467 1624.7

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that eukaryotic gene regulation is more complicated than prokaryotic gene regulation. There is more DNA present in eukaryotes and the DNA has histones and other proteins. This alone creates more steps in order for regulators to come in. Also mRNAs are cut, capped and polyadenylated all before they leave the nucleus. Not to mention the nucleus is a double membraned organelle.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that this SWI/SNF mutant was not able to function as a proper Saccharmoyces because it was involved with the structure that rearranges nucleosome position. The proper function of SWI/SNF is to remodel chromatin by rearranging nucleosome components. Also they make the histone and obviously the nucleosome able to move around on the DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that adding extra acetyl groups to nucleosome tails promotes gene activity and that removing them promotes gene inactivity. This occurs because adding acetyl groups to histones promotes the activity of remodeling mechanisms which spread out chromatin for transcription. This leads to gene activity. The deacetylation process in turn promotes other proteins that act to condense or keep condensed chromatin compact and does not allow transcription to take place.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that the attenuator is what forms the hair pin loop. The loop is when the DNA folds back on itself and stops transcription. Tryptophan has an attenuator than has a specific codon that is recognized by a ribosome.

groupTime466 29.39

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in Eukaryotes is more complex than prokaryotes. Prokaryotic.Prokaryotic gene expression is primarily controlled at the level of transcription. Eukaryotic gene expression is controlled at the levels of epigenetics, transcription, post-transcription, translation, and post-translation.Prokaryotic gene expression (both transcription and translation) occurs within the cytoplasm of a cell due to the lack of a defined nucleus; thus, the DNA is freely located within the cytoplasm. Eukaryotic gene expression occurs in both the nucleus (transcription) and cytoplasm (translation).
explainConcepts[SQ002] Loosens attachment between histone and DNA Loosens DNA strand from nucleosome core Causes reorganization of internal nucleosome components
explainConcepts[SQ003] The trp operon is regulated primarily by a repressor protein and secondarily by attenuation.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] Histone acetylation and deacetylation are essential parts of gene regulation Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one molecule o another. Deacetylation is simply the reverse reaction where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule.
phenomenonB The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonB[comment] Loosens DNA strand from nucleosome core Causes reorganization of internal nucleosome components
groupTime467 1269.7

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Prokaryotic organisms are single-celled organisms that lack a defined nucleus; therefore, their DNA floats freely within the cell cytoplasm. To synthesize a protein, the processes of transcription (DNA to RNA) and translation (RNA to protein) occur almost simultaneously. When the resulting protein is no longer needed, transcription stops. Eukaryotic cells, in contrast, have intracellular organelles that add to their complexity. In eukaryotic cells, the DNA is contained inside the cell's nucleus where it is transcribed into RNA. The newly-synthesized RNA is then transported out of the nucleus into the cytoplasm where ribosomes translate the RNA into protein.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Loosens attachment between histone and DNA Loosens DNA strand from nucleosome core Causes reorganization of internal nucleosome components
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Histone acetylation and deacetylation are essential parts of gene regulation Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one molecule o another. Deacetylation is simply the reverse reaction where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is possible in prokaryotes because transcription and translation occur at the same time on the same mRNA strand.
quantUnderstanding[SQ001] 3 -- Solid understanding: Could apply knowlege to solve basic problems.
quantUnderstanding[SQ002] 3.5
quantUnderstanding[SQ003] 2 -- Basic understanding: Could discuss or explain topic with another student.
quantUnderstanding[SQ004] 4.5

Group: Most Challenging Aspect & Study Plan

challengingConcept Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
challengingConcept[comment] Prokaryotic organisms are single-celled organisms that lack a defined nucleus; therefore, their DNA floats freely within the cell cytoplasm. To synthesize a protein, the processes of transcription (DNA to RNA) and translation (RNA to protein) occur almost simultaneously. When the resulting protein is no longer needed, transcription stops. Eukaryotic cells, in contrast, have intracellular organelles that add to their complexity. In eukaryotic cells, the DNA is contained inside the cell's nucleus where it is transcribed into RNA. The newly-synthesized RNA is then transported out of the nucleus into the cytoplasm where ribosomes translate the RNA into protein.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes. This is because eukaryotes are more complex organisms than prokaryotes. Prokaryotes have more DNA that needs to be replicated. Prokaryotes also have more organelles to copy. Further, gene regulation in prokaryotes happens mainly in transcription. However, in eukaryotes, it happens in transcription and also post transcription modification. Overall, eukaryotes are more complex organisms than prokaryotes, so gene regulation is also more complex.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning. If loop occurs in template strand during replication, DNA polymerase misses looped out nucleotides, and small insertions or deletions occur. Replication slippage is common in repeat sequences or hot spots. These contribute to hereditary diseases and they are also responsible for genetic anticipation in these diseases, for example, Fragile-X and Huntington disease.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing. This is because histone acetylation and deacetylation is the process where the lysine residue in the N-terminal tail from the histone core of the nucleosome is acetylated and deacetylated as part of gene silencing. They donate alkyl groups to amino or keto group and alter base-paring affinity, which causes transition mutations, for example, mustard gas.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes. This relates to a biological phenomena because eukaryotes are more complex organisms than prokaryotes. Prokaryotes have more DNA that needs to be replicated.

phenomenonB[comment] Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing. This relates to a biological phenomena because histone acetylation and deacetylation is the process where the lysine residue in the N-terminal tail from the histone core of the nucleosome is acetylated and deacetylated as part of gene silencing.

groupTime466 53.78

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes in a variety of ways. Many of these differences are due to the fact that eukaryotic DNA is much large than prokaryotic DNA, and because of this, eukaryotic organisms have had to develop mechanisms to compensate or work with their large DNA. One difference between gene regulation in eukaryotes and prokaryotes is that in eukaryotes, RNA polymerase doesnt recognize the promoter sequence itself, but rather the transcription factor proteins that recognize and bind the promoter sequence (TATA box) recruit the RNA polymerase after they have bound to the sequence. Another aspect of the differences between gene regulation in prokaryotes and eukaryotes is that prokaryotic systems are more adept at responding to the environment around them. Unlike in eukaryotes which have stable mechanisms of maintaining homeostasis, prokaryotes are sensitive to their environment and respond more quickly and directly to outside stimuli.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf mutant was found to be deficient in the protein that is responsible for moving histones. These proteins usually can physically move the histones, reorganize and remodel the chromosome from tightly packed to loosely packed to allow gene expression. Under various circumstances, there are two genes that determine the sex in the Saccharomyces, and depending on what nucleosomes are unpacked and flipped, one of the two alleles for mating type will be in the correct position and will thus determine the sex of the Saccharomyce.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The nucleosomes have tails that hang out of the nucleosome and are free to be acted on by other enzymes in the cells. These tails are critical to gene regulation, gene expression, and chromatin remodeling. Using the mechanism of acetylation and deacetylation, enzymes in the cell can act on these tails, which induce conformational change, either winding the histone/nucleosome complex even tighter, or relaxing the histone/nucleosome complex, allowing gene transcription and gene expression. A chromosome is considered silenced when it is packed in such a way that transcription macherinery cannot get to the gene sequences in the DNA wrapped around the histones, and this wrapping and packing is regulated by enzymes that can either use Acetylation or deacetylation of nucleosome tails to silence or turn back on a gene.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] The differences in gene regulation is one of the most interesting aspects of these topics to me. I think I like this discussion so much because it is fascinating to see how evolution, mutation, and environmental factors all have such a pivotal role in the humans we are today.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] The acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails is interesting to me because I remember learning about acetylation and deacetylation in organic chemistry, and it is interesting to now look at this mechanism from a broader perspective and look into what these chemical modifications really do in a cell.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that there are key differences in gene regulation between eukaryotes and prokaryotes. These differences have probably come up because of evolution and random mutation. I understand the nature of the genomes in eukaryotic organisms and prokaryotes are at the base of the difference in gene regulation. I understand that eukaryotes have more steps and more complex gene regulation, and I understand that this is probably because we have many more genes as well as introns to deal with.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the swi-snf mutant results in a faulty protein that cannot move the histone around on the strings of DNA. Because of this inability to physically move the histones, the DNA that has been wrapped around the histones to form nucleosomes is silenced because transcription machinery cannot reach or recognize the promoter sequence or have access to the DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand the acetylation and deacetylation of the nucleosome tails is a critical mechanism of gene regulation. Gene silencing is very common in the human chromosome, so this regulation mechanism is absolutely critical to proper develop and molecular functioning. Having the free nucleosome tails sticking out of the big, bulky nucleosome structure allows them to be acted upon by a variety of enzymes that make chemical modifications to regulate the placement and stability of nucleosome structures.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is a critical mechanism in prokaryotes, as the prokaryotic genome is a small circular strand of DNA that has genes right next to each other. I understand that without attenuation, the transcription machinery could go around the entire prokaryotic genome anytime that transcription was initiated. This would be chaotic for the cell, and it would certainly not survive. The prokaryotic mechanism of attenuation allows gene transcription to be terminated in prokaryotic cells.

groupTime466 6.2

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The reason is because eukaryotes have many types of specialized cells that have to express different genes at different times. The human body alone has something like 200 different cell types--each performing a different function. This function is dictated by what genes are being expressed. Second, eukaryotes tend to be much larger than prokaryotes. Stimuli sensed at one part of a eukaryotic body must be relayed to other cells in order for the organism to respond properly (homeostasis). This entails the need for more complex regulatory mechanisms involving hormones and other signaling molecules that must travel long distances quickly.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Histone acetylation and deacetylation are the processes by which the lysine residues within the N-terminal tail protruding from the histone core of the nucleosome are acetylated and deacetylated as part of gene regulation. Histone acetylation and deacetylation are essential parts of gene regulation. These reactions are typically catalysed by enzymes with "histone acetyltransferase" (HAT) or "histone deacetylase" (HDAC) activity. Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one molecule (in this case, Acetyl-Coenzyme A) to another. Deacetylation is simply the reverse reaction where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is a proposed mechanism of control in some bacterial operons which results in premature termination of transcription.Attenuation involves a provisional stop signal (attenuator), located in the DNA segment that corresponds to the leader sequence of mRNA. During attenuation, the ribosome becomes stalled (delayed) in the attenuator region in the mRNA leader. Depending on the metabolic conditions, the attenuator either stops transcription at that point or allows read-through to the structural gene part of the mRNA and synthesis of the appropriate protein.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than prokaryotes for a number of reasons. A major reason gene reuglation in eukaryotes is more complex is because eukaryotic DNA is wrapped around histones to form nucleosomes and the genome of eukaryotes is significantly larger than prokaryotes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Swi-snf is a very well studied remodeling complex that loosens attachments between histones and DNA in nucleosomes. This loosens DNA strands from the nucleosome core to cause reorganization of internal nucleosome components. The swi-snf mutant does not allow for the nucleosome to be repositioned.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation are essential parts of gene regulation. Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one moleculeto another and deacetylation is the reverse action where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule. Acetylation leads to greater levels of gene transcription and deacetylation leads to decreased levels of transription.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] In genetics discussion we learned about epigenetics which are caused by external or environmental factors to switch genes on or off and affect how cells read genes instead of being caused by changes in the DNA sequence. We learned about epigenetics in humans, eukaryotes, in which the nucleosomes were rearranged. Epigenetics in eukaryotes shows how much more complex gene regulation is compared to prokaryotes.
phenomenonB The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonB[comment] In genetics discussion we focused on the mutation that caused cystic fibrosis. Although the mutation for cystic fibrosis does not involve nucleosome repositioning, it is interesting to see how different mutations have different effects in the cell.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes for many reasons. One reason is that the eukaryotic genome is significantly larger than prokaryotes. Eukaryotic DNA is bound by proteins called histones to create nucleosomes. The winding of DNA around the nucleosome core contributes to DNA's packaging and also effects what genes are read for transcription. Prokaryotes lack such techniques to organize their DNA making them less complex. Prokaryotic gene expression is primarily controlled at the level of transcription where eukaryotic gene expression is controlled by epigenetics, transcription, post-transcription, translation, and post-translation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that a normal swi-snf causes reorganization of internal nucleosome components. The beta-enhanceosome is an example of a histone movement by swi-snf. The swi-snf mutants can not ferment sucrose or switch mating type. This mutant was part of a multigene complex that repositioned nucleosomes. Therefore, swi-snf mutants are deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that histone acetylation and deacetylation are the processes by which the lysine residues within the N-terminal tail protruding from the histone core of the nucleosome are acetylated or deacetylated as a part of gene regulation. These reactions are typically catalysed by the enzymes histone acetyltrasnferase and histone deacetylase. Acetylation removes the positive charge on the histones, thereby decreasing the interaction of the N-termini of histones with the negatively charged phosphate groups of DNA. This leads to higher levels of gene transcription. Deacetylation leads to lower levels of gene transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that attenuation is a proposed mechanism of control in some bacterial operons which results in premature termination of transcription. Attenuation involves a provisional stop signal (attenuator), located in the DNA segment that corresponds to the leader sequence of mRNA. During attenuation, the ribosome becomes stalled in the attenuator region in the mRNA leader. The attenuator stops transcription that that point which thus terminates the unneeded transcripts in the prokaryote.

groupTime466 22.3

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Eukaryotic cells contain much more DNA than prokaryotic cells, this DNA is associated with histones and other proteins to form highly compact chromatin structures with an enclosed nucleus. In terms of regulation, the mRNAs of the majority of eukaryotic genes have to go through posttranscriptional regulation in which the strands are spliced, capped, and polydentylated before they can leave the nucelus. In addition, translation rates can be modulated, as can the way that proteins are processed, modified, and degraded. With the histone structures and nucleosomes, transcription can be controlled by acetylation and methylation of nucleosome tails.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The SWI/SNF serves to remodel chromatin. It can loosen the attachment between histones aand DNA, resulting in the nucleosome sliding along the DNA and exposing regulatory regions. It can also loosen the DNA strand from the nucelosome core, or reorganize the internal nucelosome components. If there is a mutation in the gene, then the nucelosome can not be repositioned and the DNA in it will not be exposed to association with transcription factors and RNA polymerases. If this is the case, the genes cannot be transcribed and the proteins they code for cannot be produced.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation of a nucelosome tail will decrease the positive charge on histones by adding acetate groups, which results in a reduced affinity of the histone for DNA. This helps the chromatin conformations open up and allows for the binding of transcription regulatory proteins to DNA. Meanwhile, deacetylation would do the opposite. Histone deacetylase enzymes remove acetate groups from histone tails which will increase the negative charge on the histone and lead to increased affinity of the histone for the DNA. This makes the chromatin recondense and be unavailable for transcription.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] Enzymes are essential for both acetylation and deacetylation. Histone acetylation is catalyzed by histone acetyl transferase enzymes while histone deacetylases catalyze deacetylation activity. Without these enzymes chromatin remodeling would be highly inefficient and not be able to help eukaryotes regulate transcription.
phenomenonB The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonB[comment] If there is a mutation in the SWI-SNF gene and nucleosomes cannot be repositioned then there will be problems with accessing the DNA housed in nucelosomes. If this DNA cannot be accessed, then proteins necessary for cell survival cannot be produced and there will be problems in the cell.

This serves to weaken or impair expression of the operon. When tyrptohpan is absent, I understand that transcription will be initiated but not be subsequently terminated, instead continuing beyond the leader sequence into the structural genes. Thus I understand that attenuation ensures that genes that are not needed will not be transcribed.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotes often use operons to group genes together and enact control over them. In eukaryotes, gene regulation can occur at any step from DNA to protein. Cells can use histone modification or chromatin remodeling by SWI/SNF. They also have enhancers and silencers and various transcription factors. Finally they have posttranscriptional modification.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This mutant was found to be unable to ferment sucrose or switch mating type. It was part of a complex that repositioned nucleosomes as part of chromatin remodeling.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation makes the DNA hyperacetylated which makes the genes active and allows them to be transcribed. Deacetylation makes the DNA hypoacetylated and turns off the genes which means they will not be transcribed.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] Takes advantage of the histone tails and allows for gene regulation through acetylation. When glucose is present in yeast, galactose is not needed so the histones become deacetylated so that gal 1 is not expressed which metabolizes galactose.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] One unique form of gene regulation in eukaryotes is alternative splicing. It allows many different gene products to be made from the same sequence of DNA. Depending on which genes are kept and which are spliced, the resulting protein has a different function.

groupTime466 42.81

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Eukaryotes employ a wide range of mechanisms for altering the expression of genes. Prokaryotes typically have gene regulation that occurs primarily at the level of transcription. In eukaryotes it can occur at many levels. Eukaryotes contain much more DNA in the cells than prokaryotes do. Eukaryotic genes are located on many different chromosomes rather than just one and these chromosomes are enclosed within a double membrane bound nucleus. Eukaryotic mRNAs can have a wide range of half lives while prokaryotic mRNA tend to decay rapidly.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Swi-snf is a remodeling complex. These move or rearrange nucleosomes along the DNA. Repositioned nucleosomes make regions of the chromosomes accessible to transcription regulatory proteins. SWI-SNF works in multiple ways. The DNA histone contacts may be loosened, allowing the nucleosomes to slide along the DNA, exposing DNA regulatory regions. The path of the DNA around a nucleosome core particle may be altered. Components of the core nucleosome particle may be rearranged, resulting in a modified structure. If it is deficient in nucleosome repositioning, these will not occur.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation decreases the positive charge on histones, resulting in a reduced affinity of the histone for DNA. This may assist in the formation of open chromatin conformations which would allow binding of transcription regulatory proteins to DNA. Histone acetylation is catalyzed by HAT, which are recruited to genes by the presence of certain transcription activator proteins that bind to transcription regulatory regions. Histone deacetylases remove acetate groups from histone tails. Histone deacetylases can be recruited to genes by the presence of certain repressor proteins on regulatory regions. Acetylation affects condensation while deacetylation affects silencing.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] MOZ (Monocytic Leukemia Zinc Finger Protein), Ybf2/Sas3, Sas2 and Tip60 (Tat Interacting Protein) all make up MYST, another well known family that exhibits acetylating capabilities. This family includes Sas3, essential SAS-related acetyltransferase (Esa1), Sas2, Tip60, MOF, MOZ, MORF, and HBO1. The members of this family have multiple functions, not only with activating and silencing genes, but also effect development and have implications in human diseases. Sas2 and Sas3 are involved in transcription silencing, MOZ and TIF2 are involved with the formation of leukemic transclocation products while MOF is involved in dosage compensation in Drosophila.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Since eukaryotes can have gene regulation occur at many different levels such as alterations in DNA template, initiation of transcription, mRNA modifications and stability, and synthesis, modification, and stability of protein product, then these make it possible for them to use more types of gene regulation than prokaryotes.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation is more complex in eukaryotes in comparison to prokaryotes because eukaryotes have linear chromosomes that require modification before they can leave the nucleus and be translated into proteins. Eukaryotes also lac operons, which are the more simple derivative of gene regulation. There are also much more transcription factors involved in eukaryotic gene regulation than in prokaryotic gene regulation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This mutation occurs due to a deficiency in nucleosome repositioning. nucleosomes are responsible for wrapping and condensing chromosomes in eukaryotes, and their ability to unfold and relax plays a major role in gene expression and repression. This type of modification in swi-snf mutants result in mutants because they lack the ability to express certain genes that code for certain enzymes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation of nucleosome tails results in the DNA wrapped around the nucleosomes to relax and ultimately decondense. This decondensation allows for polymerases to enter and initiate transcription. Deacetylation does the opposite and ultimately turns off transcription by causing the chromosomes to condense.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] Acetylation on a section of DNA that codes for melanin enzymes would decondense and express melanin.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Deacetylation of a section of DNA that codes for melanin enzymes would condense and repress expression of melanin

groupTime466 20.44

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Regulation of some operons in E. coli are leaky. To compensate, a second system called attenuation has evolved. Attenuation involves a short leader sequence with areas of complementary base pairing. When sufficient gene product (amino acids and thus tRNAs for those amino acids) is available, ribosomes read through the leader sequence which allows formation of an intrinsic terminator and releases RNA polymerase from the DNA. When insufficient gene product is available, the ribosomes stall, a different secondary pairing of mRNA occurs and formation of an intrinsic terminator is prevented. RNA polymerase reads through the operon structural genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Regulation of some operons in E. coli are leaky. To compensate, a second system called attenuation has evolved. phenomenonB[comment] Because of histones that are wrapped around chromosomal DNA in eukaryotes is usually condensed during mitosis/meiosis for replication, they are deacetylated. On its own during interphase, they are acetylated and easily accessed for gene transcription.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Eukaryotic DNA is linear, unlike circular prokaryotic DNA, and eukaryotic cells also have more DNA. To densely pack this DNA, eukaryotes have chromatin complexes. These histones and coiling of DNA complicate transcription and translation, in addition to the fact that eukaryotic DNA is found inside the nucleus. Also, eukaryotes can control gene regulation at many different steps, starting at transcription, through translation, and beyond.
explainConcepts[SQ002] A yeast that is mutant in both components of the swi/snf remodeling complex cannot reposition nucleosomes. Swi and snf are two genes that make up this complex of proteins that affect gene expression by binding to DNA and repositioning the nucleosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Lysine residues can either acetylate or methylate nucleosomes. This affects how tightly the chromatin is wound around the histones, and therefore how easily the DNA can be transcribed. Altering the accessibility of the DNA in this manner can turn a gene "on" or "off." It creates many possibilities for histone variants.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Eukaryotic organisms are typically much more complex than prokaryotes. For example, the human eye alone is extremely complex and requires different genes to be expressed than a stomach tissue cell. Prokaryotes have less drastically different parts, and fewer of them. Therefore, prokaryotes need a complex system of gene regulation to achieve this complexity, especially since they also tend to have many more genes than prokaryotes.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] I think it is interesting how there is a "histone code" that is determined by what methyl or acetyl groups are added to the tail of a nucleosome. The variation of these different signatures adds another layer of complexity to eukaryotic gene expression.

groupTime466 306.6

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Like almost any other aspect of cell activity, gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than gene regulation in prokaryotes. In prokaryotes, regulation is carried out predominantly at the level of increasing or decreasing transcription. In eukaryotes, other mechanisms can act to regulate gene expression, like chromatin remodeling, alternate mRNA splicing, transportation of mRNA to the cytoplasmic ribosomes, etc. Additionally, eukaryotes have enhancers and silencers in addition to the promoters and repressors found in prokaryotes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Swi-snf is a well-studied chromatin remodeling complex. It loosens attachments between the histones, thus allowing the DNA to move away from the nucleosome core. Organisms with this mutation are unable to remodel the chromatin, meaning they are unable to switch genders (swi portion) and unable to ferment sugar (snf portion).
explainConcepts[SQ003] Active genes have nucleosomes that are rich in acetyl groups, while inactive genes have histones that are poor in acetyl groups. This happens because acetylated histones help recruit remodeling complexes that loosen chromatin for transcription. Likewise, deacetylated histones recruit complexes that can repress transcription.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Alternative splicing can cause the same strand of unprocessed mRNA to result in different protein products.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Acetylated histones represent active genes.
groupTime467 7750

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that prokaryotic and eukaryotic gene regulation differs, with eukaryotic regulation generally being more complicated. I understand that two of the largest differences stem from the fact that eukaryotic mRNA must be transported outside of the nucleus before translation can occur and the fact that eukaryotic DNA has introns, which must be excised from the mRNA before translation. In post-transcriptional processing, the mRNA can be spliced in many different ways, resulting in many different gene products. Additionally, the addition of caps and polyadenylation increases the half-life of mRNA, but variation in the half-life can act as a regulatory mechanism. Another area of eukaryotic gene regulation is chromatin remodeling, which exercises control on which genes are accessible to transcription factors and RNA polymerase. Lastly, the way in which proteins are folded is another regulatory mechanism.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that Swi-snf is a well-studied chromatin remodeling complex. It loosens attachments between the histones, thus allowing the DNA to move away from the nucleosome core. Organisms with this mutation are unable to remodel the chromatin, meaning they are unable to switch genders (swi portion) and unable to ferment sugar (snf portion).
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Active genes have nucleosomes that are rich in acetyl groups, while inactive genes have histones that are poor in acetyl groups. This happens because acetylated histones help recruit remodeling complexes that loosen chromatin for transcription. Likewise, deacetylated histones recruit complexes that can repress transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that attenuation is a way to terminate transcription after translation has already begun in prokaryotes. One example of this mechanism occurs in the tryptophan operon. When tRNA with tryptophan is readily available, the ribosome moves quickly through tryptophan codons in the leader sequence. This prevents the mRNA from forming a terminator hairpin, and transcription (as well as translation) occurs unimpaired. When tRNA with tryptophan is not readily available, however, the ribosome stalls on the tryptophan codons, allowing the mRNA to form a terminator hairpin. This signals RNA polymerase to terminate transcription, resulting in no new protein product. I understand that this process is called attenuation, and it is used to prevent unnecessary production of proteins which are already available.

groupTime466 36.72

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotic gene expression is simple and it primarily is controlled at the level of transcription. However, the more complex eukaryotic gene expression is controlled at the level of transcription, post-transcription, translation, and post-translational. Prokaryotic gene expression both transcription and translation occurs only at cytoplasm since there is no nucleus. However, in eukaryotes the transcription occurs in nucleus and translation occurs in cytoplasm.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Swi-snf is a nucleosome remodeling complex found in both eukaryotes and prokaryotes. it is a group of proteins that associate to remodel the way DNA is packaged. It is composed of several proteins and polypeptides. It possesses a DNA stimulated ATPase activity and can destabilize histone and DNA interactions in nucleosomes. However, when mutation occurs though deletion, insertion, etc the protein complex undergoes chemical and physical changes. Due to this the swi-snf complex is not able to bind to the cis factor of the AT rich content, also due to the mutation the polyA tail would cause problem for swi-snf complex for nucleosome remodeling.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome is done for gene regulation. it is the process through which lysin residue in the N-terminal tail in histone of the nucleosome are acetylated and deacetylated. Acetylation is simply adding an acetyl group on the nucleosome and deacetylation is removing the acetyl group. Acetylation takes off the positive charge on the histones and in doing so it decreases the interaction of the N terminial of histones with the negatively charged phosphate groups of DNA. Due to this the condensed chromatin becomes more relaxed and allows for greater levels of gene transcription. However, the acetylation of the nucleosome makes the histone more compact and thus allows for reduced level of gene transcription.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] Acetylation and deacetylation in our body are responsible for gene expression in our body. if the gene that needed to be expressed is not expreesed or the genes that dont need to be expressed are expreesed then it results into numerous disease. One such example is inflamattory lung disease in which the genes are expressed which causes inflamattory lung disease. another example is cancer where epigenetic marker from acetylation can be used to at least prevent cancer from happening.
phenomenonB The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonB[comment] There is evidence of swi-snf complex mutant in causing various biological phenomenon. Swi-snf nucleosome remodeling complexes use the energy of ATP to remodel nucleosomes. However, there is growing evidence that these complexes have a widespread role in tumour suppression, as inactivating mutations in several swi-snf subunits have recently been identified at a high frequency in a variety of cancers. The lethal tumors can arise in brain and kidney as well.

explainConcepts[SQ001] There are many differences in eukaryotic and prokaryotic regulation. Eukaryotic regulation is more complex, so eukaryotes can be much more diverse than proaryotes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf mutant is one of the best-studied remodeling complexes. It loosens the attachment between histones and DNA, thus exposing the DNA so the genes can be expressed.This loosening happens between the DNA and the nucleosome core. It causes reorganization of internal nucleosome components.
explainConcepts[SQ003] When nucleosome tails are acetylated, they uncoil and the adjacent genes can now be expressed, but if the tails are deacetylated, the nucleosomes grab the DNA even tighter, making gene expression in that region impossible.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Eukaryotes can regulate their genes more than prokaryotes can, thus eukaryotes can be more complex and diverse. With different genes being regulated in different ways, there are plenty of opportunities for diversity. Prokaryotes do not have as much diversity between species, but eukaryotic species are very different. Just looking at humans it is evident that gene regulation plays a large role in our lives.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] When nucleosome tails are acetylated, they uncoil and the adjacent genes can now be expressed, but if the tails are deacetylated, the nucleosomes grab the DNA even tighter, making gene expression in that region impossible. There are also mutations of the nucleosomes that make acetylation impossible, so there are multiple genes that are never expressed.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Regulation of some operons in E. coli are leaky. To compensate, a second system called attenuation has evolved. Attenuation involves a short leader sequence with areas of complementary base pairing. When sufficient gene product is available, ribosomes read through the leader sequence which allows formation of an intrinsic terminator and releases RNA polymerase from the DNA. When insufficient gene product is available, the ribosomes stall, a different secondary pairing of mRNA occurs and formation of an intrinsic terminator is prevented. RNA polymerase reads through the operon structural genes.

groupTime466 23.97

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Eukaryotic gene expression occurs in both the nucleus (transcription) and cytoplasm (translation).
explainConcepts[SQ002] It possesses a DNA-stimulated ATPase activity and can destabilise histone-DNA interactions in reconstituted nucleosomes in an ATP-dependent manner, though the exact nature of this structural change is unknown.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one molecule to another. Deacetylation is simply the reverse reaction where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule.
phenomenonA The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonA[comment] It has been found that the SWI/SNF complex (in yeast) is capable of altering the position of nucleosomes along DNA. Two mechanisms for nucleosome remodeling by SWI/SNF have been proposed. The first model contends that a unidirectional diffusion of a twist defect within the nucleosomal DNA results in a corkscrew-like propagation of DNA over the octamer surface that initiates at the DNA entry site of the nucleosome. The other is known as the "bulge" or "loop-recapture" mechanism and it involves the dissociation of DNA at the edge of the nucleosome with reassociation of DNA inside the nucleosome, forming a DNA bulge on the octamer surface.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] In eukaryotic cells, the DNA is contained inside the cell's nucleus where it is transcribed into RNA. The newly-synthesized RNA is then transported out of the nucleus into the cytoplasm where ribosomes translate the RNA into protein. The processes of transcription and translation are physically separated by the nuclear membrane; transcription occurs only within the nucleus, and translation occurs only outside the nucleus within the cytoplasm.
groupTime467 482.8

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] he regulation of gene expression can occur at all stages of the process . Regulation may occur when the DNA is uncoiled and loosened from nucleosomes to bind transcription factors (epigenetics), when the RNA is transcribed (transcriptional level), when the RNA is processed and exported to the cytoplasm after it is transcribed (post-transcriptional level), when the RNA is translated into protein (translational level), or after the protein has been made (post-translational level).
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] It is composed of several proteins products of the SWI and SNF genes as well as other polypeptides.[3] It possesses a DNA-stimulated ATPase activity and can destabilise histone-DNA interactions in reconstituted nucleosomes in an ATP-dependent manner, though the exact nature of this structural change is unknown.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Acetylation has the effect of changing the overall charge of the histone tail from positive to neutral.The mechanism for acetylation and deacetylation takes place on the NH3+ groups of Lysine amino acid residues. These residues are located on the tails of histones that make up the nucleosome of packaged dsDNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is a regulatory mechanism used in bacterial operons to ensure proper transcription and translation. In bacteria, transcription and translation are capable of proceeding simultaneously. The need to prevent unregulated and unnecessary gene expression can be prevented by attenuation, which is characterized as a regulatory mechanism.

explainConcepts[SQ001] In prokaryotic cells, the control of gene expression is mostly at the transcriptional level. In eukaryotic cells, the DNA is contained inside the cell's nucleus where it is transcribed into RNA. The newly-synthesized RNA is then transported out of the nucleus into the cytoplasm where ribosomes translate the RNA into protein.
explainConcepts[SQ002] SWI/SNF is capable of altering the position of nucleosomes along DNA.[5] Two mechanisms for nucleosome remodeling by SWI/SNF have been proposed.[6] The first model contends that a unidirectional diffusion of a twist defect within the nucleosomal DNA results in a corkscrew-like propagation of DNA over the octamer surface that initiates at the DNA entry site of the nucleosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation are essential parts of gene regulation. These reactions are typically catalysed by enzymes with histone acetyltransferase activity. Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one molecule to another. Deacetylation is simply the reverse reaction where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule.
phenomenonA The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonA[comment] SWI/SNF is a nucleosome remodeling complex found in eukaryotes and prokaryotes.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Acetylation and deacetylation are the processes by the lysine residues within the N-terminal tail protruding from the histone core of the nucleosome are acetylated and deacetylated as part of gene regulation.
groupTime467 612.68

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] In prokaryotic cells, the control of gene expression is mostly at the transcriptional level. To synthesize a protein, the processes of transcription and translation occurs simultaneously. When the resulting protein is no longer needed, transcription stops. Transcription occurs only within the nucleus, and translation occurs only outside the nucleus within the cytoplasm. The regulation of gene expression can occur at all stages.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] SWI/SNF is a nucleosome remodeling complex found in eukaryotes and prokaryotes. The DNA loop propagate across the surface of the histone octamer in a wave-like manner, resulting in the repositioning of DNA without changes in the total number of histone.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] DNA becomes more tightly wrapped around the histone cores, making it harder for transcription factors to bind to the DNA. This leads to decreased levels of gene expression and is known as gene silencing. The combination of acetylation and phosphorylation have shown effects on the chromosomes overall structural condensation level
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuators are characterized by the presence of stop signals within the DNA sequence that can result in either transcriptional-attenuation or translational-attenuation. transcriptional and translational attenuation. The process of attenuation involves the presence of a stop signal that indicates premature termination. Translational-attenuation is characterized by the misfolding of the Shine-Dalgarno sequence. The Shine-Dalgarno sequence, responsible for ribosomal binding to allow proper translation, is inaccessible because it is folded into a hairpin-loop structure, thus, translation cannot occur. Transcriptional-attenuation is characterized by the presence of an attenuator within the DNA sequence that results in formation of mRNA-stem loops that prevent further transcription from occurring. The non-functional RNA produced prevents proper transcription

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotic gene regulation is primarily controlled at the level of transcription. Eukaryotic gene regulation is controlled in multiple areas, including transcription, post-transcriptionally, translation, and post-translationally. Eukaryotic gene expression must also take care of the nucleosomes that potentially block a gene from being read. Changes can be made to the mRNA chain, or to proteins that have just been made by a ribosome.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf remodeling complex loosens attachments between a histone and the DNA and loosens the DNA from the nucleosome core. This causes reorganization of internal nucleosome components. The swi-snf mutant is unable to ferment sucrose and also unable to switch mating types unlike normal yeast. This is a result of the protein complexes being unable to move so that different DNA is able to be read.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Hyperacetylation of nucleosome tails occurs in active genes and make the nucleosome rich in acetyl groups. Inactive genes have histones that are low in acetyl groups and are therefor hypoacetylated. Acetylated histones may recruit remodeling complexes that decondense chromatin for transcription. Deacetylated histones may recruit other protein complexes that repress transcription.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] If a nucleosome tail is acetylated, this will alter the overall structure of the histone code. Transcription factors are able to recognize not only specific DNA sequences but also specific histone codes which would affect what genes are being transcribed if different transcription factors are being "called" for.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Some prokaryotes have a lac operon that controls whether proteins are transcribed for and translated to break down glucose when it is in the cell. The different parts of the operon may be mutated which would affect how much of the proteins are made in different situations. One example of this is if the repressor cannot bind allolactose, transcription will always be off. If there is a mutation in which the repressor cannot bind the operator, then transcription will always be on. These different parts all affect whether transcription occurs for one set of proteins but these processes involve more parts in eukaryotes.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Prokaryotic gene regulation is primarily controlled at the level of transcription. knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The swi-snf remodeling complex loosens attachments between a histone and the DNA and loosens the DNA from the nucleosome core. This is a result of the protein complexes being unable to move so that different DNA is able to be read.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Hyperacetylation of nucleosome tails occurs in active genes and make the nucleosome rich in acetyl groups. I understand that this does not occur in prokaryotes because there is no chromosomal organization like in eukaryotes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Regulation of some operons in E. coli are leaky. To compensate, a second system called attenuation has evolved. Attenuation involves a short leader sequence with areas of complementary base pairing. When sufficient gene product (amino acids and thus tRNAs for those amino acids) is available, ribosomes read through the leader sequence which allows formation of an intrinsic terminator and releases RNA polymerase from the DNA. When insufficient gene product is available, the ribosomes stall, a different secondary pairing of mRNA occurs and formation of an intrinsic terminator is prevented. RNA polymerase reads through the operon structural genes. Attenuation is possible in prokaryotes because transcription and translation occur at the same time on the same mRNA strand.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation is more complicated in eukaryotes than in prokaryotes. This is due to several factors. Prokaryotes only have gene regulation at transcription, but eukaryotes have gene regulation at the DNA template, translation, through mRNA and protein modifications and stability as well as transcription.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The wild type gene of swi/snf codes for a chromatin remodeling complex that can move nucleosomes to one side so that the DNA is exposed and can be transcribed. Mutants of this gene are unable to move the nucleosomes off of the TATA box, so the genes on the DNA are unable to be transcribed.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Histone tails are often not packaged into the nucleosome and are thus key targets for gene regulation. Acetylation adds acetyl groups on to the histone tail, opening the chromatin and allowing genes to be transcribed. This turns genes ON. Deacetylation, however, removes the acetyl groups causing the chromatin to condense and thus silencing the genes.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Eukaryotes are more sophisticated in gene regulation than prokaryotes. However, this is not the process in which eukaryotes are more complex than prokaryotes. Eukaryotes have more complicated processes of DNA replication, transcription, and translation as well.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] This is very similar to another aspect of gene regulation: methylation. However in methylation, methyl groups are added to nucleosomes with the opposite effect. Methylation turns genes off while demethylation of nucleosomes turns genes ON.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] This topic is fairly clear to me as I understand that mutants of this gene are unable to move the nucleosomes off of the TATA box, so the genes on the DNA are unable to be transcribed.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand this concept as I know that Acetylation adds acetyl groups on to the histone tail, opening the chromatin and allowing genes to be transcribed. This turns genes ON. Deacetylation, however, removes the acetyl groups causing the chromatin to condense and thus silencing the genes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is a process that regulates leaky operons via a leader sequence. An example is in the tryptohan operator. When trp is scarce, an mRNA folds into a hairpin loop, allowing transcription to proceed past the antiterminator region and the entire mRNA is transcribed. However, if there is excess trp present, the mRNA structure forms a terminator hairpin which stops transcription.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in Prokaryotes consists largely of transcriptional regulation where eukaryotic regulation consists of regulation at all stages of the process of DNA>Product. Eukaryotes have nucleosomes that can be methylated or acetylated. The mRNA transcripts can be modified in many ways including the addition of a 5 prime cap or a poly A tail. Additionally, mRNA transcripts can be spliced in many different ways, increasing the number of possible gene products. There are even more methods beyond this.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi/snf product is involved in nucleosome and histone remodeling complex. Some types of yeast can use this product to switch their mating types in response to certain factors.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation is associated with increased gene expression while deacetylation is associated with deacreased gene expression. The acetyl groups neutralize the positive charge on the histone groups of the nucleosomes, resulting in a more accessible molecule to polymerases.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] The complexity of eukaryotic gene regulation allows for different levels of gene regulation at each point in the process of transcription and translation. Most evidently is the ability to splice genes in different ways, producing many times more gene products than there are genes in any particular eukaryote.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Acetylation and deacetylation of histones allows for expression and repressed expression, respectively. In females, for example, the deactivated X chromosome, the Barr body, is found to be highly unacetylated, contributing to its genetic insignificance.

Gene regulation in Prokaryotes consists largely of transcriptional regulation where eukaryotic regulation consists of regulation at all stages of the process of DNA>Product. Eukaryotes have nucleosomes that can be methylated or acetylated. The mRNA transcripts can be modified in many ways including the addition of a 5 prime cap or a poly A tail. Additionally, mRNA transcripts can be spliced in many different ways, increasing the number of possible gene products. Activators and repressors can serve additionally to modify expression of certain genes.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation are forms of genetic regulation in eukaryotes. Prokaryotic life does not use acetylation or deacetylation of histones because prokaryotes do not have nucleosomes. Acetylation is associated with increased gene expression while deacetylation is associated with deacreased gene expression. In females, for example, the deactivated X chromosome, the Barr body, is found to be highly unacetylated, contributing to its genetic insignificance. The acetyl groups neutralize the positive charge on the histone groups of the nucleosomes, resulting in a more accessible molecule to polymerases.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is often used as a mechanism to prevent the complete expression of genes whose transcription has been initiated despite the current state of repression. As in transcription termination, hairpin loops can be formed to stop the previously initiated transcription.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotic gene regulation is only controlled at transcription, while eukaryotic gene regulation is controlled with epigenetics, transcription, post-transcription, translation, and post-translation. Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Given the overall complexity of Eukaryotes compared to prokaryotes, there is no surprise that gene regulation would be more complex. Eukaryotes have gene regulation in almost every stage in transcription from inside the nucleus to the production of proteins. Eukaryotes also have different binding sites and different transcription factors and enzymes that are incorporated in the process of transcription as well.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The presence of nucleosomes makes the transcription process difficult in some cases and next to impossible in others. the SWI/SNF complex takes part in chromatin remodeling and loosens the histones from the DNA strand; thus allowing for transcription. Without this complex, the DNA strand would not be able to be transcribed because of the presence of histones, or only sections of DNA would be transcribed (which could lead to a nonfunctional protein)
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation can cause the chromatin to tighten around histones and become silenced or loosen around histones and become active. This is why cells on our tongue are different from cells on our liver. The tighter certain sections of chromosomes are, the more inactive and vice versa. This topic is crucial when it comes to understanding the human body.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] As stated earlier, in order to know and understand how cells are different in their function yet the same in their composition, one must fully understand Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails. Those sections of DNA that are wound too tightly will become inactive and those that are loosened around the histone will become active. This explains the great variety of cells and their functions.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Over my time in biology courses, I have realized that eukaryotes are more complex than prokaryotes. This is also applied when it comes to gene regulation. Since DNA is transcribed inside of the nucleus yet translated outside of the nucleus, the levels of gene regulation highly vary from step by step of the DNA replication process compared to prokaryotes in which transcription and translation occur simultaneously.

groupTime466 77.61

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation is more complex in eukaryotes compared to prokaryotes for numerous reasons. For one, eukaryotes contain a greater amount of DNA, which is associated with histones and other proteins. Additionally, in eukaryotes have to be regulated, undergoing splicing, capping, and polyadenylation, before being transported out of the nucleus. mRNAs also have a wide range of half-lives, and can be modulating during translation, protein processing, modification, and degradation. Also, genes on numerous eukaryotic chromosomes are enclosed in a double membrane nucleus.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The SWI/SNF complex is a remodeling complex that can act in several different ways to cause DNA to be exposed from the nucleosome and transcribable. It was discovered that this complex aids in nucleosome repositioning after the effects of mutant Saccharomyces SWI/SNFs were observed. SNI mutants are defective in the ability to switch mating type, and SNF mutants are defective in the ability to ferment sucrose (sugar-nonfermenting). Mutants possessing both SWI/SNF are deficient in nucleosome repositioning, indicating that SWI/SNF plays a crucial role as a remodeling complex.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Histones may be modified by acetylation, whereby the enzyme histone acetyltransferase (HAT) adds an acetyl group to the positively charged amino group. Doing so neutralizes the positive charge of the histones and negates their attraction to DNA. This allows the chromatin to open up and become available for transcription. On the other hand, deacetylation occurs when histone deacetylases (HDACs) remove acetate groups from histone tails, causing the chromatin to close back up around the histones. Deacetylation causes the chromosome to once again condense and effectively silences those genes for the time being.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] Acetylation and deacetylation depends on the charges of the interacting histone proteins and DNA, a concept explored in chemistry and physics.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Histone deacetylation can turn off gene transcription in the galactose metabolism pathway of yeast.
groupTime467 2882.51

I also understand that eukaryotes have to be regulated, undergoing splicing, capping, and polyadenylation, before being transported out of the nucleus. mRNAs also have a wide range of half-lives, and can be modulating during translation, protein processing, modification, and degradation. Additionally, I understand that genes on numerous eukaryotic chromosomes are enclosed in a double membrane nucleus.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the SWI/SNF complex is a remodeling complex that can act in several different ways to cause DNA to be exposed from the nucleosome and transcribable. I understand that it was discovered that this complex aids in nucleosome repositioning after the effects of mutant Saccharomyces SWI/SNFs were observed. I understand that SNI mutants are defective in the ability to switch mating type, and SNF mutants are defective in the ability to ferment sucrose (sugar-nonfermenting). In conclusion, I understand that mutants possessing both SWI/SNF are deficient in nucleosome repositioning, indicating that SWI/SNF plays a crucial role as a remodeling complex.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that histones may be modified via acetylation, whereby the enzyme histone acetyltransferase (HAT) adds an acetyl group to the positively charged amino group. I understand that doing so neutralizes the positive charge of the histones and negates their attraction to DNA, allowing the chromatin to open up and become available for transcription. On the other hand, I also understand that deacetylation occurs when histone deacetylases (HDACs) remove acetate groups from histone tails, causing the chromatin to close back up around the histones. I understand that deacetylation causes the chromosome to once again condense and effectively silences those genes for the time being.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that regulation of some operons in E. coli are leaky, and attenuation has evolved to compensate. I understand that attenuation consists of a short leader sequence with areas of complementary base pairing. I understand that when sufficient gene products are available, ribosomes read through the leader sequence which allows formation of an intrinsic terminator and releases RNA polymerase from the DNA. I also understand that when insufficient gene products are available, the ribosomes stall, a different secondary pairing of mRNA occurs, and formation of an intrinsic terminator is prevented. I understand that the RNA polymerase can then read through the operon structural genes and enable the production of terminators.

explainConcepts[SQ001] In the simplest terms, prokaryotic gene regulation is controlled mainly at the transcription phase while eukaryotic regulation occurs in all phases. Since prokaryotes don't have a defined nucleus, this happens in the cytoplasm, but eukaryotes are able to regulate genes in both the cytoplasm and nucleus.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Not covered in class and haven't read about this in the book yet.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation adds an acetyl functional group to a molecule while Deacetylation removes an acetyl functional group from a molecule. Acetylation decreases reaction with the N termini of DNA and therefore letting the structure of the DNA condense and relax in order to create a structure that is more agreeable to transcription. Deacetylation makes DNA wrap tightly around the histone cores, leading to gene silencing.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] The acetylation of histones can attract proteins to elongated chromatin that has been marked by acetyl groups, providing a platform for protein binding.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Gene silencing by deacetylation is a common research method used to repress the expression of a gene without completely eliminating it when it might be vital to an organism's survival.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex because there are transcription factors instead of operons. The transcription factors help induce or reduce the amount of regulation in the gene. For example, enhancers will enhance the regulation of genes and may increase gene expression. Activators will activated the transcription, and repressors will stop or pause transcription. For prokaryotes, there are operons. The operons have different structural genes that will produce different enzymes which will determine whether or not beta galactosidase.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The mutant gene causes the disruption of nucleosomes which makes the yeast deficient in nucleosome repositioning. Some genes cause defects in the complex which alters its function.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation adds an acetyl group which exposed the DNA and increases gene expression. Deaceylation is the removal of an acetyl group which tightens the nucleosome and DNA is not exposed therefore gene expression is decreased.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Eukaryotes have transcription factors and prokaryotes have operons with structural genes.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Acetylation and deacetylation increases and decreases gene expression.
groupTime467 1413.81

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Eukaryotes have transcription factors: enhancers, activators, repressors. Histone acetylation and deacetylation happens within eukaryotes. Prokaryotes have operons like lac operon with structural genes like lacY lacZ and lacA. They each have a part in how lactose is transported in the cell and whether or not beta galactosidase can be made.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] This mutant has a disruption in the nucleosome and this is why it is deficient in nucleosome positioning.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand acetylation and deacetylation increase or decrease gene expression because the nucleosome is exposed when an acetyl group is added, increasing expression. DNA is not exposed when acetyl group is taken away, decreasing the expression of genes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] When transcripts are unneeded, there is a premature termination of transcription so that the prokaryotic cell will not waste energy on unneeded transcripts. The premature stop signal is called an attenuator.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] There are a greater amount of DNA associated with histones and other proteins in euakaryotes than prokaryotes. in eukaryotes, mRNA must be spliced, capped, and polyadenylated before leaving the nucleus. Genes from many chromosomes are enclosed in a double membrane nucleus in eukaryotes. Eukaryotic mRNAs have a wide range of half lives.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Swi/Snf is a remodeling complex that loosens the attachment between the histone and DNA, loosens DNA strand from nucleosome core, and causes reorganization of internal nucleosome components. Swi/snf mutants were unable to switch mating types and ferment sucrose.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Active genes are hyperacetylated (have histone groups rich in acetyl groups) and inactive genes are hypoacetylated (have histone groups poor in acetyl groups). Acetylated histones recruit remodeling complexes that decondense chromatin for remodeling and deacetylated histones recruit other protein complexes that repress transcription.
phenomenonA The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonA[comment] To study the swi/snf mutants, researchers chose yeast that were unable to ferment sucrose.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Eukaryotes have more complex cell structures and a different mode of cell division. A more complex gene regulation is needed to account for this.
