groupTime466 31.55

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation is different between eukaryotes and prokaryotes. Prokaryotic gene expression is mainly controlled at the transcription level. Eukaryotic gene expression is controlled at many different places like epigenetics, transcription, post-transcription, translation, and post-translation. Prokaryotic regulation occurs within the cytoplasm because there is a lack of a nucleus. Eukaryotic gene expression occurs in both the nucleus and cytoplasm. Regulation can occur at all stages of the process, like when the DNA is uncoiled and loosened from nucleosomes to bind transcription factors. It can also be regulated when the RNA is transcribed or post-transcription, when RNA is made into proteins, or after the proteins have been made.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Swi-Snf is a complex found in both eukaryotes and prokaryotes and is a group of proteins that remodel the way DNA is package and can destabilise histone-DNA interactions. the swi-snf allows yeast to change mating types so the mutation is deficient in repositioning required to switch types.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation changes the amount of chromosome condensation, which then affects gene silencing. These reactions are catalysed by enzymes histone acetyltransferase (HAT) and histone deacetylase (HDAC). Adding or removing acetyl groups to histone tails condenses/ de-condenses the chromosomes, which then regulates transcription of genes.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is different and more complex than in prokaryotes. This makes sense in the biological world because eukaryotes are more complex than prokaryotes. Eukaryotic transcription and translation is much more complex, making the regulation also more complex. Eukaryotes have organelles and compartments, which make their processes more difficult and complex.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Acetylation and deacetylation relates to the biological phenomenon of phenotypic expression and the differences among humans. The amount of acetylation affects the expression of different genes. Some genes will be silenced and others expressed.
groupTime467 3886.04

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand a decent amount about the differences of eukaryotic and prokaryotic gene regulation. I need to spend a little more time understanding the exact mechanisms as to how they are different. I know that the fact that eukaryotes are more complex automatically causes other things in eukaryotes more complex.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I really do not know much about the ski-snf complex but i do know that it is found in both eukaryotes and prokaryotes. it is a group of proteins that remodel the way DNA is package and can destabilise histone-DNA interactions. the swi-snf allows yeast to change mating types so the mutation is deficient in repositioning required to switch types. But I do not really know how this complex works.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that acetylation and deacetylation changes chromosome condensation, which then affects gene silencing. I understand that the enzymes histone acetyltransferase (HAT) and histone deacetylase (HDAC) add or delete acetyl groups to histone tails. Adding or removing acetyl groups to histone tails condenses/ de-condenses the chromosomes, which then regulates transcription of genes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I know that attenuation is a regulatory mechanism used in bacterial operons for proper transcription and translation. The need to prevent unregulated and unnecessary gene expression can be prevented by attenuation, which is characterized as a regulatory mechanism. However, i do not know much about attenuation or how it works. I need to look into this topic more. The process of attenuation involves the presence of a stop signal that indicates premature termination. The stop signal, referred to as the attenuator, prevents the proper function of the ribosomal complex, stopping the process. The attenuator is transcribed from the appropriate DNA sequence and its effects are dependent on the metabolic environment. In times of need, the attenuator within the mRNA sequence will be bypassed by the ribosome and proper translation will occur. However, if there is not a need for a mRNA molecule to be translated but the process was simultaneously initiated, the attenuator will prevent further transcription and cause a premature termination. Hence, attenuators can function in either transcription-attenuation or translation-attenuation.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is generally more complex than regulation in prokaryotes because these two types of cells differ in their structure and function in various ways. First of all, eukaryotes have many more genes than prokaryotes, and these genes are spread among many chromosomes within the organism, while prokaryotes do not have as many genes to spread across multiple chromosomes. Furthermore, the genes of a prokaryote are all contained within an individual chromosome. In prokaryotes, groups of genes that produce similarly-functioning proteins are organized into operons, while these genes are not organized in operons of eukaryotes. Ultimately, the greater complexity of eukaryotic cells signifies that these organisms require a more complex system of gene regulation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is a complex system of various subunits that requires the energy of ATP to control gene expression within organisms. This mutant is typically responsible for repositioning nucleosomes, which aids in the process of modulating gene expression within the organism. However, in Saccharomyces, this ability is deficient, leading to lack of control of gene expression within the organism.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation is the process in which an acetyl group is added to a molecule; deacetylation is simply the reverse process. When an acetyl group is added or removed from a nucleosome tail, chromosome condensation and gene silencing can be affected because this process often causes the DNA to be more tightly or loosely packed together in the long run.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Species of prokaryotes do not typically possess any phenotypic differences, while eukaryotes, especially humans, tend to have many differences in their features. The complexity of gene regulation in eukaryotes in comparison with the more simple gene regulation of prokaryotes may have an effect on this variation.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Due to acetylation or deacetylation of nucleosome tails, certain genes within organisms can be corrected through gene silencing if they are mutated or deficient.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is much more complex than in prokaryotes for a number of reasons. There is a greater amount of DNA that is associated with histones and other proteins. mRNAs must be spliced, capped, and polyadenylated before being transported to the cytoplasm. Genes on numerous chromosomes are enclosed in a double membrane nucleus. mRNAs have a wide range of half lifes. Modulation of mRNA translation, protein processing, modifications, and degradation are much more complex.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swo-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning, which leads to the yeast not being able to ferment sucrose or switch mating types. This because the mutation does not allow for the chromatin to be remodeled by allowing the DNA to separate from the histones and nucleosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation of nucleosome tails recruits remodeling complexes that decondenses chromatin for transcription. This renders the gene active. Deacetylation of DNA recruits other protein complexes that repress transcription. This condenses chromatin and inactivates genes.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] Gene regulation in eukaryotes is much more complex than in prokaryotes which is related to the biological basis of many disorders. Due to the expression of a specific gene, a disorder can arise in an individual. This can be due to many factors.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] An important biological phenomenon related to acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails is that it can activate or deactivate specific genes. This can cause some genes to be expressed or repressed.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotic gene expression is primarily controlled at the level of transcription. Eukaryotic gene expression is controlled at the levels of epigenetics, transcription, post-transcription, translation, and post-translation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The DNA of eukaryotic cells is spooled around large histone protein complexes, forming nucleosomes that make up the basis for a high-order packaging structure called chromatin. Compared to naked DNA, nucleosomal DNA is less accessible to regulatory proteins and regulatory processes. The exact positions of nucleosomes therefore influence several cellular processes, including gene expression.
explainConcepts[SQ003] egulation. These reactions are typically catalysed by enzymes with "histone acetyltransferase" (HAT) or "histone deacetylase" (HDAC) activity. Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one molecule (in this case, Acetyl-Coenzyme A) to another. Deacetylation is simply the reverse reaction where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.

groupTime467 440.15

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Eukaryotic cells, in contrast, have intracellular organelles that add to their complexity. In eukaryotic cells, the DNA is contained inside the cell's nucleus where it is transcribed into RNA. The newly-synthesized RNA is then transported out of the nucleus into the cytoplasm where ribosomes translate the RNA into protein.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] In eukaryotic cells, long linear stretches of DNA must be contained within the very small space of the nucleus. Every human cell, for example, contains about 2 m of linear DNA, whereas the diameter of the nucleus is only 5 to 20 m (135). This creates a packaging problem that all eukaryotic cells are faced with: long molecules of stiff, negatively charged DNA need to be folded into the confined space of the nucleus. Moreover, the folded DNA has to remain accessible for various cellular processes, such as replication and transcription. To achieve this, cells coil DNA around histones.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Acetylated histones, octameric proteins that organize chromatin into nucleosomes and ultimately higher order structures, represent a type of epigenetic marker within chromatin. Acetylation removes the positive charge on the histones, thereby decreasing the interaction of the N termini of histones with the negatively charged phosphate groups of DNA. As a consequence, the condensed chromatin is transformed into a more relaxed structure that is associated with greater levels of gene transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuators are characterized by the presence of stop signals within the DNA sequence that can result in either transcriptional-attenuation or translational-attenuation. Transcriptional-attenuation is characterized by the presence of an attenuator within the DNA sequence that results in formation of mRNA-stem loops that prevent further transcription from occurring. The non-functional RNA produced prevents proper transcription.

groupTime466 26.69

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotic transcription and translation occur simultaneously in the cytoplasm, and regulation occurs at the transcriptional level. Eukaryotic gene expression is regulated during transcription and RNA processing, which take place in the nucleus, and during protein translation, which takes place in the cytoplasm. Further regulation may occur through post-translational modifications of proteins. so one is not more difficult than the other, just different.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The primary function of the SWIB protein domain is to aid gene expression. In yeast, it expresses certain genes, in particular BADH2, GAL1, GAL4, and SUC2. It works by increasing transcription. It has ATPase activity, which means it breaks down ATP, the basic unit of energy currency. This destabilises the interaction between DNA and histones. This disrupts chromatin and opens up the transcription-binding domains. Transcription factors can bind to this site, leading to an increase in transcription.
explainConcepts[SQ003] enzymatic modifications acetylation, and methylation, primarily occur at N-terminal histone tails. Such modifications affect the binding affinity between histones and DNA, and thus loosening and tightening the condensed DNA wrapped around histones, e.g., Methylation of specific lysine residues in H3 and H4 causes further condensation of DNA around histones, and thereby preventing binding of transcription factors to the DNA leading to gene repression. On contrary, histone acetylation relaxes chromatin condensation and exposes DNA for TF binding, leading to increase gene expression
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] Access to nucleosomal DNA is governed by two major classes of protein complexes,Covalent histone-modifying complexes of acetylation and methylation.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] Chromatin remodeling plays a central role in the regulation of gene expression by providing the transcription machinery with dynamic access to an otherwise tightly packaged genome. Further, nucleosome movement by chromatin remodelers is essential to several important biological processes, including chromosome assembly and segregation, DNA replication and repair
groupTime467 537.89

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than in regulation in prokaryotes
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The protein interactions of the SWI/SNF complex with the chromatin allows binding of transcription factors and therefore increase in transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Chromatin remodeling is the dynamic modification of chromatin architecture to allow access of condensed genomic DNA to the regulatory transcription machinery proteins, and thereby control gene expression. Such remodeling is principally carried out by 1) covalent histone modifications by specific enzymes, i.e., histone acetyltransferases (HATs), deacetylases, methyltransferases, and kinases, and 2) ATP-dependent chromatin remodeling complexes which either move, eject or restructure nucleosomes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is a regulatory mechanism used in bacterial operons to ensure proper transcription and translation. In bacteria, transcription and translation are capable of proceeding simultaneously. The need to prevent unregulated and unnecessary gene expression can be prevented by attenuation, which is characterized as a regulatory mechanism.

groupTime467 1080.34

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] With prokaryotic gene expression, transcription and translation occur in the cytoplasm because there isn't a nucleus, therefore the DNA is also located in the cytoplasm. The level of control is at the transcriptional level, because if a prokaryotic organism needs a certain protein, it will produce until it no longer needs it. With eukaryotic gene expression, transcription happens in the nucleus and translation happens in the cytoplasm. Eukaryotic cells have many smaller organelles that contribute to creating protein by taking DNA, transforming into mRNA, then tRNA, then finally protein. Transcription factors are also necessary in order to help with regulation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Chromatin remodeling is the process of reorganizing nucleosomes on DNA in order to allow transcription factors more access to the chromosome. A type of nucleosome reorganization is switching the mating type, but this does not occur when the swi mutant is present. In a different experiment, snf was found to be the mutant that affected yeast's ability to ferment sugar. swi/snf is a mutant that can neither switch mating type nor ferment sugar.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] With deacetylation, DNA is tightened around the histones, which makes it more difficult for transcription factors to bind to the DNA. Lack of transcription factors means less gene expression which means gene silencing. Acetylation weakens the binding of the nucleosome, making transcription easier to occur. Acetylation loosens the structure of chromatin which also helps increase levels of transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attentuation is a mechanism in operons that help to stop transcription and translation of a certain protein that is no longer needed for the organism. It is a type of regulatory mechanism. An example is the tryptophan operon where tryptophan molecules will bind to the repressor in order to block RNA polymerase from following through with transcription.

groupTime466 24.27

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation in eukaryotes has been proven to be more complex than regulation in prokaryotes. For starters prokaryotic gene expression is controlled mainly at the transcription level, whereas eukaryotic gene expression includes transcriptional regulation, epigentics, post-transcriptional regulation, and translational, and post-translational regulation. Basically, eukaryotic cells can regulation gene expression at almost any point within the central dogma. Also, prokaryotic gene expression occurs in the cytoplasma whereas eukaryotic gene expression occurs within the nucleus. This difference allows prokaryotic cells to begin translation before trascription has been completed. In eukaryotic cells, transcription is temporally and spatially seperated. Transcription occurs in the nucleus and translation occurs in the cytoplasm at the ribosome. Also, transcription in eukaryotes has to be completed before translation can begin.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf complex in eukaryotic Saccharomyces is an ATP-dependent chromatin remodeling complex used by cells to stimulate or repress gene transcription. The swi-snfi complex binds to both the DNA and the nucleosome but does not do so in a site-specific fashion. When swi-snf is absent, as seen in the mutant eukaryote, mRNA levels are significantly decreased. Basically, the swi-snf complex remodeles chromosomes making genes more accessible for transcription by loosening DNA strands or by reorganizing internal nuclosome components. When this complex is absent, this form of gene regulation is also absent making DNA less capable of being transcribed.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails in histones can affect chromosome condensation and gene silencing. This process involves the addition or removal of an acetyl group to the lysine residues within the N-terminal tails of the nucleosomes that make up histones. This process helps regulate gene expression. Depending on how acetylated or deactylated the histones in a chromosome are. The enzyme responsible for the acetylation of these proteins is HAT, or histone acetyltransferase, and the enzyme responsible for deacetylating these proteins is HDAC, histon deacetylase. Acetylation relaxes and uncondenses chromatin whereas deacetylation recondenses chromatin. When the chromatin is relaxed DNA binding proteins are better able to interact with the genes activating gene transcription.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] The fact that gene regulation in eukaryotes and prokaryotes is vastly different is really pretty interesting to me. I think its really cool that prokaryotes can start translation before transcription is completed. Normally, I feel like with cell processes one has to be completed before the next can start. Also, this concept is important to larger biological phenomenon because the more complex gene regulation found in eukaryotes allows these organisms to be more complex as well. As humans, we are in need of great gene regulation that isnt quite necessary in the more simplistic prokaryotic cells.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] This topic relates to a broader biological phenomenon known as epigentics. This semester we have spent a lot of time learning about his phenomenon. Chemical remodeling of nucleosomes is one of the main forms of regulation in epignetics depending on how acetylated or deacetylated parts of a are chromosoms determines which portions of it will be expressed or not expressed. Altered expression and mutations of genes that encode the enzyme HDAC, which deacetylates histones, have been linked to tumor development. Therefore, HDACs can be used as therapeutic targets for cancer treatment.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that gene regulation in eukaryotes is far more complex than that found in prokaryotes. I understand that whereas in prokaryotes gene regulation occurs mainly at the transcriptional level, in eukaryotic cells gene regulation can occur at almost any point in the central dogma. This allows for more complex regulation that includes things like epignetics and deacetylation/acetylation of histones. I understand that this type of complex regulation is necessary for the formation of eukaryotic organsims for they themselves are far more complex that prokaryotic organisms.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the swi-snf complex found in Saccharomyces is used in gene regulation. Its function includes remodeling of chromatin to make regions of the chromosome more or less condensed. This allows for different gene regulation that can be altered depending on the environment in which this organism is found. I understand that when this complex is absent, which is a condition found in some mutants, then mRNA production is reduced significantly because the chromatin is more tightly bound and less open for interactions with DNA binding proteins. Therefore, gene expression in these mutants an be greatly affected.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that acetylation and deacetylation are important mechanisms in gene regulation. There are two enzymes, HAT and HDAC, that are important for these two processes. I understand that histone acetyltransferase is the enzyme involved with the acetylation of the N-terminal tails of nucleosomes, and that histonde deacetylase is the enzyme involved with deacetylating these N-terminal histone tails. Acetylation relaxes chromatin, whereas deacetylation recondenses the chromatin. When chromatin is condensed, it is called heterochromatin in unable to interact with DNA binding proteins making it "silent" in gene expression. When chromatin is relaxed, or in its euchromatin form, it is able to interact with DNA binding proteins making it open for gene expression. Overall, I understand that these two processes are extremely important in gene regulation for these reasons.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that attenuation is a process that has evolved to compensate for the sometimes leaky regulation of E. Coli operons. I understand that this process involves a small leader sequences that has areas of complementary base pairing. When there is a sufficient amount of gene product such as trp, ribosomes will read the leader sequences which will cause an intrinsic terminator to form causing the release of RNA polymerase from the DNA. This represses operons. I also understand that when gene product is found in insuffiencent amounts, the ribosome will stop and mRNA pairing occurs which prevents the formation of a terminator. Therefore, the operon is not repressed.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotes only regulate genes on the transcriptional level, while eukaryotes modify genes with epigenetics, during and after transcription, and during and after translation. Prokaryotes only perform regulation in the cytoplasm, while eukaryotes do in a variety of environments.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi/snf mutation causes the yeast cells to be unable to produce working proteins that modify chromatin. Nucleosome repositioning is the methylation of portions of genes in order to deactivate them.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation of tails removes the positive charge. Without a positive charge, the tails are less reactive and loosen up. Once loosened, the DNA strand can be transcribed.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] This is one way that regulation in controlled by epigenetics. During development, certain chemical environments can permanently alter the chromatin positioning, which can lead to the lack or overexpression of genes later on in the life of the individual.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] Eukaryotes can regulate genes spatially. By looping out segments of DNA, genes are brought closer to promoters and enhancers, which significantly increase transcriptional levels.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails occur when acetyl groups are either added to or taken away from the nucleosome tails of the ends of chromosomes. knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuators are characterized by the presence of stop signals within the DNA sequence that can result in either transcriptional-attenuation or translational-attenuation. Transcriptional-attenuation is characterized by the presence of an attenuator within the DNA sequence that results in formation of mRNA-stem loops that prevent further transcription from occurring. The non-functional RNA produced prevents proper transcription. Translational-attenuation is characterized by the misfolding of the Shine-Dalgarno sequence. The Shine-Dalgarno sequence, responsible for ribosomal binding to allow proper translation, is inaccessible because it is folded into a hairpin-loop structure, thus, translation is inaccessible because it is folded into a hairpin-loop structure, thus, translation cannot occur.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation is significantly more complex in eukaryotes than in prokaryotes for a number of reasons. First, the genome being regulated is significantly larger. The E. coli genome consists of a single, circular chromosome containing 4.6 Mb. This genome encodes approximately 2000 proteins.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In molecular biology, SWI/SNF (SWItc, is a nucleosome remodeling complex found in both eukaryotes and prokaryotes. In simpler terms, it is a group of proteins that associate to remodel the way DNA is packaged. It is composed of several proteins products of the SWI and SNF genes as well as other polypeptides.It possesses a DNA-stimulated ATPase activity and can destabilise histone-DNA interactions in reconstituted nucleosomes in an ATP-dependent manner, though the exact nature of this structural change is unknown.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Histone acetylation and deacetylation are the processes by which the lysine residues within the N-terminal tail protruding from the histone core of the nucleosome are acetylated and deacetylated as part of gene regulation.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Gene regulation is significantly more complex in eukaryotes than in prokaryotes for a number of reasons. First, the genome being regulated is significantly larger. The E. coli genome consists of a single, circular chromosome containing 4.6 Mb. This genome encodes approximately 2000 proteins.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] In molecular biology, SWI/SNF , is a nucleosome remodeling complex found in both eukaryotes and prokaryotes. In simpler terms, it is a group of proteins that associate to remodel the way DNA is packaged. It is composed of several proteins products of the SWI and SNF genes as well as other polypeptides. It possesses a DNA-stimulated ATPase activity and can destabilise histone-DNA interactions in reconstituted nucleosomes in an ATP-dependent manner, though the exact nature of this structural change is unknown.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Histone acetylation and deacetylation are essential parts of gene regulation. These reactions are typically catalysed by enzymes with "histone acetyltransferase" (HAT) or "histone deacetylase" (HDAC) activity. Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one molecule to another. Deacetylation is simply the reverse reaction where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is a proposed mechanism of control in some bacterial operons which results in premature termination of transcription and which is based on the fact that, in bacteria, transcription and translation proceed simultaneously.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotes have circular, double stranded DNA, while eukaryotes have DNA organized around histones into nucleosomes. So, prokaryotes have a much more simple gene regulation. Eukaryotes can alter the structure of their DNA while prokaryotes rely solely on operons.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Swi-snf mutants can not ferment sucrose or switch mating types. The gene mutation occurred within a multi-gene region that coded for a complex that allowed for the loosing of histones around DNA, allowing exterior DNA to interact with interior DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation works by neutralizing the positive charge on lysine residues of the histone. The histones relax the DNA, and allow for mRNA transcription to occur. Hypoacetylation can silence genes as the DNA becomes very condensed.

groupTime466 90.31

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In prokaryotes, the gene regulation system consists of the lac operon and the trp operon. In these systems, structural genes are linked by one regulatory gene and promoter and operator sequences. When these systems fail, the system of attenuation is used. The eukaryotic gene regulation system is more complex because it can occur in transcription and anytime after as in during translation, mRNA transport, ribosome regulation, or protein folding and synthesis.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf mutant shows that this complex is involved in chromatin remodeling. It involves a single protein loosening the DNA strand from the nucleosome to reorganize the chromosome for replication or transcription. In Saccharomyces, the swi-snf mutant is manipulated to study this complex.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Active genes are hyper or over acetylated while inactive genes are hypo or under acetylated. These processes of acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails is regulated by HAT and HDAC enzymes, respectively. When HDAC removes the acetyl group, it can silence genes while acetylated histone tails can talk to proteins that condense chromatin.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] I am interested in the function of the lac operon compared to the many cis-acting and trans-acting sequences for eukaryotes. I am interested in the lac operon and how the mutation or silencing of one sequence affects the expression of all the lac structural genes, Z Y and A.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] This concept is interesting because it shows how the addition of one acetyl group to the histone tails in chromosomes can affect the chromosome by activating or silencing genes in the DNA.
groupTime467 831.7

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] In prokaryotes, genes are regulated by operon systems such as the lac operon and the trip operon. If this system is leaky, then the attenuated system is used to intrinsically terminate the sequences. In these operons, the structural genes are controlled by one repressor that can bind to the operator and prevent DNA polymerase from binding. In eukaryotes, the regulation of genes is more complex because regulation can occur during transcription as well as after. For example, mRNA may not be allowed to leave the nucleus, alternative splicing may occur, ribosome regulation may occur, or proteins may be modified, all regulating the expression of genes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] This mutant is studied in Saccharomyces because this organism is haploid, thus making it easier to study. When this mutant is present, the yeast cannot reposition nucleosomes, which can prevent the availability of the DNA. For example, this complex can be involved in chromatin remodeling because it involves a single protein loosening the DNA strand from the nucleosome to reorganize the chromosome, but a mutation causes the nucleosome to remain intact and prevent replication and transcription.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Acetylation and deacetylation occur by the HAT and HDAC enzymes, respectively. When histone tails are acetylated, the genes can be activated; however hypoacetylation can inactivate genes. These acetylated histones can talk to proteins to condense the chromatin. Basically, these two processes can alter the shape or folding of the chromosome, which can prevent or allow the transcription of the DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is the secondary system in prokaryotes that comes into play when the operon is leaky or is allowing DNA polymerase to get through. The attenuator is found just inside the operator and tries to stop stuff like polymerase from getting through so it forms a hairpin to stall translation and prevent unneeded transcripts from being made in prokaryotes.

quantUnderstanding[SQ003] 2 -- Basic understanding: Could discuss or explain topic with another student.

explainConcepts[SQ003] Nucleosome make up histones. Acetylation decreases the positive charge on histone, resulting in a reduced affinity of the histone of DNA. By deacetylating the histone tails, the DNA becomes more tightly wrapped around the histone cores, making it harder for transcription factors to bind to the DNA. This leads to decreased levels of gene expression and is known as gene silencing.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Histone acetylation and deacetylation are essential parts of gene regulation. Acetylation is the process where an acetyl functional group is transferred from one molecule to another. Deacetylation is simply the reverse reaction where an acetyl group is removed from a molecule. I understand by by deacetylating the histone tails, the DNA becomes more tightly wrapped around the histone cores, making it harder for transcription factors to bind to the DNA. This leads to decreased levels of gene expression and is known as gene silencing.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is a proposed mechanism of control in some bacterial operons which results in premature termination of transcription and which is based on the fact that, in bacteria, transcription and translation proceed simultaneously. Attenuation involves a provisional stop signal (attenuator), located in the DNA segment that corresponds to the leader sequence of mRNA. During attenuation, the ribosome becomes stalled in the attenuator region in the mRNA leader. Depending on the metabolic conditions, the attenuator either stops transcription at that point or allows read-through to the structural gene part of the mRNA and synthesis of the appropriate protein.

groupTime466 41.98

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] There are various reasons as to why gene regulation is much more complex in an eukaryotic organism than a prokaryotic organism. For instance due to the fact that eukaryotes are multi-cellular organisms, they have more DNA in comparison to the prokaryotic or unicellular organisms which requires more extensive packaging of that DNA. Hence, eukaryotic gene regulation deals with removing and re-attaching the histone proteins that allow condensation of the DNA; processes such as acetylation, deacteylation, and methylation are all processes that affect the amount of histone proteins that are wrapped inside DNA thus affecting gene expression. Another difference that results in the complexity of gene regulation in eukaryotes is the fact that transcription and translation do not occur simultaneously since there is a nucleus that holds the chromosomal DNA (transcription occurs in the nucleus while translation occurs in the cytoplasm). This causes another level of gene regulation in eukaryotes that is not present in prokaryotes.Therefore, these physiological differences in between the eukaryotes and prokaryotes results in the high level of complexity of gene regulation in eukaryotes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] I currently do not know much information about this topic, but I do know that the SWI-SNF mutants got their name since the mutants are unable to to switch between mating types depending upon the given environmental conditions (SWI) and they are also unable to ferment sucrose ( SNF= sucrose non-fermenting). Furthermore, the since the mutants are deficient in nucleosome repositioning, I am assuming there is either a possibility of hyper-expression or hypo-expression of a particular gene sequence. I do plan on learning more about this topic soon especially since I am highly unaware about the experiment associated with these mutants and the effect the mutations has on nucleosome repositioning.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The processes of acetylation and deacetylation enable the chromosomes to decondense and re-condense thus allowing and increase and a decrease in gene expression, respectively. Acetylation is the process of adding an acetyl group to a histone through the enzyme called histone acetyltransferase or HAT. The addition of an acetyl group (negatively charged) to the positively charged histone protein results in the histone protein to become neutral thus losing its affinity for the negatively charged DNA (Phosphate backbone)and thus allows the unraveling or uncoiling of some of the genetic material from its associated proteins. This process results in an increase in gene expression since there are no histone proteins that condense the genetic material to that extreme as before. On the other hand, deacetylation is a process in which decreases the expression of a gene through the enzyme called Histone deacteyltransferase or Hdac which is the reverse process of what is discussed above. This enzyme removes acetyl groups that are previously attached and allows the re-condensation of the genetic material which then suppresses gene expression and enables the silencing of a gene sequence. In conclusion, the attachment and removal of acetyl groups enables the variation in gene expression of certain gene sequences within the genome of the organism.
phenomenonA Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonA[comment] I find histone modifications especially in consideration to epigenetic markers very intriguing so processes such as acetylation and deacetylation fascinate me. I am interested in what type of cell regulation or cell metabolic pathway triggers the attachment and detachment of acetyl groups on the ends of nucleosome tails through the enzymes HAT and Hdac, respectively. I am also interested if hyperacetylation of a gene sequence and even hypoacetylation of certain gene sequences that control tumor suppressors can lead to cancer causing agents or cancerous tumors.
phenomenonB Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonB[comment] I find the complexity of gene regulation in eukaryotes interesting because it fascinates me that how certain mechanisms are created in result of these "barriers" and creates accommodations to increase the efficiency of processes such as gene regulation.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that gene regulation is much more complex in eukaryotes than eukaryotes since there is more involvement of more genetic material, presence of a nucleus in eukaryotes which separates the transcription and translation process, and the varying half-life of mRNAs, and more. The presence of a nucleus inhibits DNA from exiting the organelle thereby not allowing the simultaneous process of transcription and translation as well. Furthermore, gene regulation has multiple "steps" which is found in eukaryotes since it is highly regulated in eukaryotes ( gene regulation sites occur during transcription, post-transcription, during translation, and post-translation and also includes histone modifications); whereas, prokaryotic gene regulation is controlled simply transcritionally. All in all, many factors result in the complexity that is noticed in the process of gene regulation and expression in eukaryotes when compared to prokaryotes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] A swi-snf mutant was selected since it lacked the ability to switch between mating types and ferment surcose like non-mutant Saccharomyces. This mutant was selected and isolated from mutants of the yeast that could perform one function and not the other. Once the swi-snf mutant was selected for, it was noticed that the mutant was a part of a multigene family that essentially repositions nucleosomes. I am not sure much about this topic since I was absent in lecture since I was sick that day and I could not find anything related to the swi-snf mutants in the version of the textbook that I use. I plan on asking a few friends about this topic to see if they can assist me.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Acetylation and deacteylation are controlled by two enzymes known as HAT (Histone Acetyltransferase)and HDAC (Histone Deacetyltransferase, respectively. In acetylation, acetyl groups are attached to the lysine residues that are commonly found at the tails of nucleosomes. These lysine residues give the histone proteins a positive charge which allows the proteins to wrap around the DNA molecule since the DNA molecule is negatively charged due to the sugar-phosphate backbones. Once the acetyl group is attached to the lysine end of the nucleosome tail, it neutralizes the histone protein with its negative charge. Thus, the nucleosome complex uncoils to a certain extent which allows the DNA sequence to be expressed with an ease since the DNA is not tightly coiled to the protein. However, deacteylation affects chromosome condensation as well by condensing the DNA sequence more which enables the gene sequence to be more silenced in a manner since the DNA is so tightly coiled to the histone proteins which causes a barrier for the process of transcription. Therefore, deacteylation like methylation results in the silencing of DNA sequence.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Attenuation is a process that is found in prokaryotes that results in the early termination of a transcript. For instance in the trp operon, attenuation is similar to a fail-safe if the active repressor molecule fails to attach to the operator site when tryptophan levels are high. In this operon, upstream to the functional genes is a leader sequence which codes for four palindromic sequences in which the first and the second region are complementary to each other while the third and fourth region are complementary to each other. The ribosome is able to pass through the first region with ease but as it gets to the second region, it is unable to move past which hinders RNA Polymerase from creating a proper mRNA and a stem loop is formed between the two complementary regions 3 and 4 and a poly U sequence follows the region 4 which acts as an intrinsic terminator which is characteristic in the process of attenuation. This causes the RNA Polymerase to fall off and prematurely terminate the gene sequence since the termination occurs prior to reaching the functional genes.

groupTime466 24.73

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Gene regulation is more complex in eukaryotes compared to prokaryotes for numerous reasons. For one, eukaryotes contain a greater amount of DNA, which is associated with histones and other proteins. Additionally, in eukaryotes have to be regulated, undergoing splicing, capping, and polyadenylation, before being transported out of the nucleus. mRNAs also have a wide range of half-lives, and can be modulating during translation, protein processing, modification, and degradation. Also, genes on numerous eukaryotic chromosomes are enclosed in a double membrane nucleus
explainConcepts[SQ002] The SWI/SNF complex is a remodeling complex that can act in several different ways to cause DNA to be exposed from the nucleosome and transcribable. It was discovered that this complex aids in nucleosome repositioning after the effects of mutant Saccharomyces SWI/SNFs were observed. SNI mutants are defective in the ability to switch mating type, and SNF mutants are defective in the ability to ferment sucrose (sugar-nonfermenting). Mutants possessing both SWI/SNF are deficient in nucleosome repositioning, indicating that SWI/SNF plays a crucial role as a remodeling complex.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Histones may be modified by acetylation, whereby the enzyme histone acetyltransferase (HAT) adds an acetyl group to the positively charged amino group. Doing so neutralizes the positive charge of the histones and negates their attraction to DNA. This allows the chromatin to open up and become available for transcription. On the other hand, deacetylation occurs when histone deacetylases (HDACs) remove acetate groups from histone tails, causing the chromatin to close back up around the histones. Deacetylation causes the chromosome to once again condense and effectively silences those genes for the time being.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] This relates to many aspects of biology where eukaryotes exhibit more complexity than their prokaryotic counterparts.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] This can explain Barr bodies in humans.

I understand that attenuation involves a short leader sequence with areas of complementary base pairing. I know when sufficient gene product (amino acids and thus tRNAs for those amino acids) is available, ribosomes read through the leader sequence which allows formation of an intrinsic terminator and releases RNA polymerase from the DNA. I understand that when insufficient gene product is available, the ribosomes stall, a different secondary pairing of mRNA occurs and formation of an intrinsic terminator is prevented. This would cause RNA polymerase reads through the operon structural genes.

explainConcepts[SQ001] As we've seen with most topics this semester, eukaryotes are more complex in gene regulation than prokaryotes just as they are more complex in just about every other way. For example, the greater complexity of eukaryotic cells can be seen in the fact that each structural gene has its own promoter and is transcribed independently. Since prokaryotes are single cell, they don't have cell specific gene expression.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The swi-snf remodeler acts in several different ways. It can loosen the attachment between histones and DNA. They can also loosen the DNA from strand from the nucleosome core. Therefore, a mutation in these causes a deficiency in nucleosome repositioning.
explainConcepts[SQ003] HATs catalyze histone acetylation while HDACs remove acetate groups to accomplish the opposite. Both of these can be recruited by transcription activator proteins while certain activator proteins can actually carry out HAT activity on their own without the need of these extra enzymes.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.

phenomenonB The swi-snf mutant in the eukaryote Saccharomyces is deficient in nucleosome repositioning.
phenomenonB[comment] Swi-snf mutations are interesting to me because the swi-snf reposition histones to make DNA more available to be read which can lead to DNA replication which is a biological phenomenon that I find personally interesting.

groupTime466 4.92

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Prokaryotic gene expression is primarily controlled at the level of transcription. Eukaryotic gene expression is controlled at the levels of epigenetics, transcription, post-transcription, translation, and post-translation. Prokaryotic gene expression (both transcription and translation) occurs within the cytoplasm of a cell due to the lack of a defined nucleus; thus, the DNA is freely located within the cytoplasm. Eukaryotic gene expression occurs in both the nucleus (transcription) and cytoplasm (translation).
explainConcepts[SQ002] The SWI/SNF complex (in yeast) is capable of altering the position of nucleosomes along DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Acetylation removes the positive charge on the histones, thereby decreasing the interaction of the N termini of histones with the negatively charged phosphate groups of DNA. As a consequence, the condensed chromatin is transformed into a more relaxed structure that is associated with greater levels of gene transcription.
phenomenonA Gene regulation in eukaryotes is more complex than regulation in prokaryotes.
phenomenonA[comment] A major difference in eukaryotic and prokaryotic gene expression is the presence in eukaryotes of a nuclear membrane, which prevents the simultaneous transcription and translation that occurs in prokaryotes. Whereas, in prokaryotes, control of transcriptional initiation is the major point of regulation, in eukaryotes the regulation of gene expression is controlled nearly equivalently from many different points.
phenomenonB Acetylation and deacetylation of nucleosome tails affects chromosome condensation and gene silencing.
phenomenonB[comment] The acetylation of histones is regulated by two highly conserved classes of histone enzymes, histone acetyltransferases and histone deacetylases, which catalyze the addition and removal, respectively, of acetyl groups on histone lysine residues. Reversible histone acetylation and deacetylation are highly regulated processes that are crucial for chromatin reorganization and the regulation of gene transcription in response to extracellular conditions. The balance between the acetylation and deacetylation of histones serves as a key regulatory mechanism for gene expression and governs numerous developmental processes and disease states.

Eukaryotic gene expression occurs in both the nucleus (transcription) and cytoplasm (translation).

Transcriptional-attenuation is characterized by the presence of an attenuator within the DNA sequence that results in formation of mRNA-stem loops that prevent further transcription from occurring. The non-functional RNA produced prevents proper transcription.
